<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06300152 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06300152 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: LaFontaine  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; HOCKEY; TRADE; MULTIPLE; MEN  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Buffalo Sabres snatched holdout center Pat LaFontaine from the New YorkIslanders on Friday, but they sacrificed one of their brightest young stars todo it.;   The Sabres obtained LaFontaine, left wing Randy Wood and defensemanRandy Hillier from the Islanders for centers Pierre Turgeon, and Benoit Hogue,right wing Dave McLlwain and defenseman Uwe Krupp.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HOLDOUT LAFONTAINE TRADED TO BUFFALO  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related story on P. 4D of this section  </MEMO><TEXT>     The Islanders also made a major deal with the Chicago Blackhawks, sendingcenter Brent Sutter (the team's captain) and left wing Brad Lauer to Chicagofor left wing Steve Thomas and center Adam Creighton, players who combined for41 goals and 64 assists for the Blackhawks last season.;   But the key figuresin all the trading activity were Turgeon and LaFontaine.;   Turgeon, the firstplayer selected in the 1987 NHL entry draft, had 32 goals and 47 assists forthe Sabres last season and had eight points (two goals, six assists) in hisfirst eight games this season. But the Sabres believe they obtained one of thetop five players in the league in LaFontaine, who has scored 287 NHL goalssince joining the Islanders late in the 1983-84 season after being the thirdoverall choice in the 1983 entry draft.;   &quot;I'm sure this was a shock forPierre,&quot; said John Muckler, the director of hockey operations for the Sabres.&quot;But when you have a chance to get a player of Pat LaFontaine's caliber, youhave to make the deal.&quot;;   LaFontaine, a 54-goal scorer during the 1989-90season, had 41 goals and 44 assists for the Islanders last season, but becameunhappy when the team refused to renegotiate his $425,000 contract. When theseason ended, he said he would not return to the Islanders unless the team wassold, and he reportedly rejected an offer worth $6 million over four years.;  LaFontaine was not in uniform for the Sabres when they met the Sharks onFriday night, but he is expected to join the Sabres in time for a game Sundayagainst the Hartford Whalers.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  MIKE WEAVER, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Buffalo, N.Y.  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911026  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  348  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, October 26, 199100300152,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>